Carl Edward Dobkins Jr.  (January 13, 1941 – April 8, 2020) was an American singer and songwriter, best known for his 1959 hit, "My Heart Is an Open Book", which went to No.3 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart.
The group sang together for approximately eight years.
Dobkins then recorded sessions for Decca in Nashville, Tennessee, which included "My Heart is an Open Book" in 1959, which reached No. 3 on the pop chart and number 11 on the R&B chart.
He also served in the United States Army Reserve for six months.
When reissued,  "If You Don't Want My Lovin'" reached number 67 later the same year.
Dobkins had two other Hot 100 entries: "Lucky Devil" (number 25, 1959), and "Exclusively Yours" (number 62, 1960).

He appeared fourteen times as a guest on Dick Clark's American Bandstand, and toured with such singers as Bobby Vee, Frankie Avalon, and Jan & Dean.

Dobkins attended Hughes High School in the late 1950s, but moved to Mt Healthy High School graduating in 1959.
